            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this profit calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you calculate profit, profit margin, markup and
                break-even units for up to three pricing scenarios at once. It
                supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Forward calculations from <strong>cost &amp; price</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Reverse calculations from a target <strong>margin</strong> or
                  <strong>markup</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Adjustments for <strong>discounts, fees and taxes</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Break-even analysis using your <strong>fixed costs</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Profit</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Profit} = \text{Revenue} - \text{Total Cost}\)</p>
                <p>For one unit:</p>
                <p>\(\text{Unit Profit} = P - C\)</p>
                <p>For multiple units:</p>
                <p>\(\text{Total Profit} = (P - C) \times Q - F\)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(P\) = price per unit</li>
                  <li>\(C\) = cost per unit</li>
                  <li>\(Q\) = quantity sold</li>
                  <li>\(F\) = fixed costs</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>2. Profit margin</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Margin} = \dfrac{\text{Profit}}{\text{Revenue}} \times
                  100\%\)
                </p>
                <p>Per unit:</p>
                <p>\(\text{Margin} = \dfrac{P - C}{P} \times 100\%\)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>3. Markup</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Markup} = \dfrac{\text{Profit}}{\text{Cost}} \times
                  100\%\)
                </p>
                <p>Per unit:</p>
                <p>\(\text{Markup} = \dfrac{P - C}{C} \times 100\%\)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>4. Price from target margin</strong></p>
                <p>Given cost \(C\) and target margin \(m\) (as a decimal):</p>
                <p>\(P = \dfrac{C}{1 - m}\)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>5. Price from target markup</strong></p>
                <p>Given cost \(C\) and target markup \(k\) (as a decimal):</p>
                <p>\(P = C \times (1 + k)\)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>6. Break-even quantity</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Break-even units} = \dfrac{F}{P - C}\)</p>
                <p>
                  where \(F\) is fixed cost, \(P\) is price per unit and \(C\)
                  is cost per unit.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you sell a product for $80 that costs you $50, and you
                expect to sell 200 units. You also have $1,000 of fixed costs.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Unit profit = 80 − 50 = $30</li>
                <li>Total profit before fixed costs = 30 × 200 = $6,000</li>
                <li>Total profit after fixed costs = 6,000 − 1,000 = $5,000</li>
                <li>Profit margin = 30 ÷ 80 × 100 = 37.5%</li>
                <li>Markup = 30 ÷ 50 × 100 = 60%</li>
                <li>Break-even units = 1,000 ÷ 30 ≈ 33.3 → 34 units</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Profit calculator FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between profit, margin and markup?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Profit is the money left after subtracting all costs from
                    revenue. Profit margin expresses that profit as a percentage
                    of revenue, while markup expresses it as a percentage of
                    cost. For the same sale, markup is always numerically higher
                    than margin.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Which is better to use: margin or markup?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Internally, many finance teams plan using profit margin
                    because it ties directly to the income statement.
                    Operational teams (sales, purchasing) often think in markup.
                    The important thing is to be consistent and avoid mixing
                    them up. This calculator shows both so you can translate
                    between them.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is the break-even calculation?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The break-even units are exact under the assumptions you
                    enter: a single selling price, constant unit cost and fixed
                    costs that do not change with volume. In real life, volume
                    discounts, step costs and capacity limits can shift the true
                    break-even point, so treat it as a planning estimate.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this for services, SaaS or digital products?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. Treat each subscription, license or project as a
                    “unit”. Use your variable delivery cost per unit (support,
                    hosting, payment fees, contractor time) as the cost per
                    unit, and your subscription or project price as the selling
                    price.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How should I handle taxes in profit calculations?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    If sales tax or VAT is collected on top of your price and
                    passed through to the government, exclude it from revenue
                    and costs. If taxes are included in the advertised price,
                    you can enter the tax rate in the calculator so it removes
                    the tax portion and shows your net revenue and profit.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
