s you $50, and you expect to sell 200 units. You also have $1,000 of fixed costs. Unit profit = 80 − 50 = $30 Total profit before fixed costs = 30 × 200 = $6,000 Total profit after fixed costs = 6,000 − 1,000 = $5,000 Profit margin = 30 ÷ 80 × 100 = 37.5% Markup = 30 ÷ 50 × 100 = 60% Break-even units = 1,000 ÷ 30 ≈ 33.3 → 34 units Profit calculator FAQ What is the difference between profit, margin and markup? Profit is the money left after subtracting all costs from revenue. Profit margin expresses that profit as a percentage of revenue, while markup expresses it as a percentage of cost. For the same sale, markup is always numerically higher than margin. Which is better to use: margin or markup? Internally, many finance teams plan using profit margin because it ties directly to the income statement. Operational teams (sales, purchasing) often think in markup. The important thing is to be consistent and avoid mixing them up. This calculator shows both so you can translate between them. How accurate is the break-even calculation? The break-even units are exact under the assumptions you enter: a single selling price, constant unit cost and fixed costs that do not change with volume. In real life, volume discounts, step costs and capacity limits can shift the true break-even point, so treat it as a planning estimate. Can I use this for services, SaaS or digital products? Yes. Treat each subscription, license or project as a “unit”. Use your variable delivery cost per unit (support, hosting, payment fees, contractor time) as the cost per unit, and your subscription or project price as the selling price. How should I handle taxes in profit calculations? If sales tax or VAT is collected on top of your price and passed through to the government, exclude it from revenue and costs. If taxes are included in the advertised price, you can enter the tax rate in the calculator so it removes the tax portion and shows your net revenue and profit. About the author Ugo Candido builds 